{{other uses|Favorite Son (disambiguation){{!}}Favorite Son}} {{confused|Fortunate Son}}

A '''favorite son''' (or a '''favorite daughter''') is a [[politics|political]] term.

* At the quadrennial American national political party conventions, a state delegation sometimes nominates and votes for a candidate from the state, or less often from the state's region, who is not a viable candidate. The technique allows state leaders to negotiate with leading candidates in exchange for the delegation's support.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19280112&id=HMsaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4ksEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1498,440704&hl=en |title=How 'Favorite Son' Politics Works |date=January 12, 1928 |newspaper=[[The Pittsburgh Press]] |via=Google News Archive Search }}</ref> The technique was widely used in the 19th and early 20th centuries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19600130&id=v91LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zooDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7345,1724319&hl=en|title=How Term 'Favorite Son' Got Started in Politics |date=January 30, 1960 |via=Google News Archive Search |newspaper=The Free Lance-Star}}</ref> Since nationwide campaigns by candidates and binding [[primary election]]s have replaced [[brokered convention]]s, the technique has fallen out of use,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19710920&id=vbVSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fH8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7269,4614679&hl=en|title=No Demo Favorite Sons |date=September 20, 1971 |via=Google News Archive Search|newspaper=[[The Deseret News]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Byron E. |last=Shafer |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAQ_cWsAW-cC&pg=PA71&dq=%22Favorite+son%22+politics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJ4cSE0cbJAhXuooMKHVHqAJ04ChDoAQgbMAA#v=onepage&q=%22Favorite%20son%22%20politics&f=false|title=Bifurcated Politics: Evolution and Reform in the National Party Convention|publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn= 9780674072565 |date=1988 }}</ref> as party rule changes in the early 1970s required candidates to have nominations from more than one state.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Y7NCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA202&ots=XpAFPNdiQd&dq=%22favorite+son%22+candidacies&pg=PA202#v=onepage&q=%22favorite+son%22+candidacies&f=false|title=Elections A to Z|first1=Dave|last1=Tarr|first2=Bob|last2=Benenson|date=22 October 2013|publisher=CQ Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>
* A politician whose electoral appeal derives from her or his native state, rather than her or his political views is called a "favorite son".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19600703&id=oIFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AQUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1939,3967594&hl=en|title=Favorite Son Idea is Devised to Put State in Strong Position at Convention |newspaper=Ocala [[Star-Banner]] |via=Google News Archive Search |date=July 3, 1960 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19680529&id=pWtPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SQUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2863,4751547&hl=en|title=Smathers Gets Favorite Son Candidate Nod |newspaper=Ocala Star-Banner |via=Google News Archive Search |date=May 29, 1968 }}</ref> For example, in the [[United States]], a presidential candidate will [[List of major-party United States presidential candidates who lost their home or resident state|usually]] win the support of her or his home [[U.S. state|state(s)]].<ref>{{cite news  |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1915&dat=19390804&id=PE81AAAAIBAJ&sjid=a3EFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1038,2634598&hl=en |title=Favorite Son Groups Will be Numerous at 1940 Convention of Democrats |newspaper=[[The Day (New London)]] |via=Google News Archive Search |date=August 4, 1939}}</ref>
* Especially in parliamentary systems, a "favorite son" is a party member to whom the party leadership is likely to assign a prominent role, for example, [[Paul Martin]] while [[Jean Chrétien]] was the [[Prime Minister of Canada]], or [[Gordon Brown]] while [[Tony Blair]] was the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]].

